3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"GMX calculates funding rates hourly based on the premium/discount between the perpetual price and Chainlink oracle feeds for SOL. Unlike CEX funding mechanisms, GMX's oracle dependency means rates reflect broader market conditions rather than platform-specific order flow imbalances. The funding payment flows between long and short positions occur every hour, with rates typically ranging from -0.01% to 0.01% per hour during normal market conditions."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","SOL","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SOL/USDT on GMX presents compelling arbitrage opportunities due to the oracle-CEX price differential and Solana's high volatility. The hourly funding frequency creates more granular arbitrage windows compared to 8-hour CEX cycles, while GMX's battle-tested infrastructure since 2021 provides reliable execution for high-frequency strategies."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SOL/USDT funding rates on GMX have historically exhibited more volatile swings during Solana network events and ecosystem developments compared to Bitcoin or Ethereum pairs. During the FTX collapse in November 2022, funding rates spiked to extreme negative levels as shorts dominated, creating significant arbitrage opportunities against Binance and OKX. The oracle-based pricing mechanism has generally kept GMX rates within 20% deviation from major CEX platforms, though brief spikes to 50-100% deviations occur during high volatility periods. Summer 2023 data shows SOL funding rates averaging -0.002% hourly, with standard deviation of 0.008%."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Cross-Platform Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"GMX's oracle dependency creates systematic arbitrage opportunities when CEX order books lead oracle price updates during volatile Solana moves. The most profitable setups occur when Binance or Bybit SOL futures show funding rates diverging by more than 0.01% from GMX's hourly rate. Gas costs on Arbitrum (typically $2-5 per transaction) must be factored against position sizes, making strategies most viable above $10,000 position sizes. Advanced arbitrageurs exploit the 1-hour vs 8-hour funding frequency differential by taking opposite positions on GMX and funding-favorable CEX platforms."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations and Oracle Dependencies"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"GMX's reliance on Chainlink oracles introduces unique risks where oracle lag during extreme SOL volatility can create temporary price dislocations of 1-3%. The GLP/GM liquidity model means large SOL trades face price impact, though this is less pronounced than on smaller DEXs. Counterparty risk differs from CEX platforms as smart contract bugs could affect position settlement, though GMX's $500M+ TVL and multi-year track record provide confidence. Cross-chain arbitrage between Arbitrum and Avalanche GMX deployments adds bridge risk and 10-20 minute settlement delays that must be considered in strategy timing."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How does GMX's hourly funding frequency affect SOL arbitrage strategies?","answer":"GMX's hourly funding payments create 8x more settlement opportunities compared to standard 8-hour CEX cycles. This allows for more granular arbitrage positioning and faster capital turnover, but requires monitoring positions more frequently and accounting for gas costs on each settlement."},{"question":"What makes SOL funding rates different on GMX versus centralized exchanges?","answer":"GMX uses Chainlink oracle prices rather than internal order book dynamics, meaning funding rates reflect broader market premiums rather than platform-specific trading activity. This can create systematic differences during periods when Solana network events affect sentiment differently across trading venues."},{"question":"How significant is price impact when trading large SOL positions on GMX?","answer":"Price impact varies with GLP composition but typically ranges from 0.1-0.5% on $100K+ SOL trades during normal conditions. During high volatility or low GLP depth, impact can reach 1-2%, making pre-trade impact estimation crucial for arbitrage profitability calculations."},{"question":"Can I arbitrage between GMX Arbitrum and Avalanche deployments for SOL?","answer":"Yes, but cross-chain arbitrage requires bridging assets between networks, adding 10-20 minutes settlement time and bridge fees of 0.1-0.3%. This strategy works best for larger divergences that persist beyond immediate arbitrage, typically during network-specific events affecting one chain more than the other."}]}]
